0. Dataset Introduction and Description¶

Obesity is a medical issue where excessive amounts of body fat result in increased risk of diseases and health problems, including but not limited to heart disease, diabetes, and high blood pressure [1]. Worldwide obesity has nearly tripled since 1975, and most of the world's population lives in countries where being overweight or obese kills more people than being underweight - it's not just a first-world country problem anymore [2]. The rise of this problem can be attributed to a variety of trends, including increasing use of technology while sedentary, less time spent on physical activities, and increased intake of foods that are high in fat and sugar. Although there have been some programs that encourage healthy living to stave off obesity (Michelle Obama's Let's Move! campaign comes to mind), obesity often gets much less attention and resources than other acute and chronic diseases.

The dataset we picked for our logistic regression extension task contains data for estimation of obesity levels in individuals from the countries of Mexico, Peru, and Colombia, based on collected information on eating habits, lifestyle choices, and physical characteristics [3]. This information was collected via an online survey and preprocessed to handle missing and atypical data. There were 485 initial responses, and respondents were labelled with one of 7 weight categories (Underweight, Normal, Overweight I, Overweight II, Obesity I, Obesity II, and Obesity III) based on WHO standards of BMI and Mexican normativity, using the equation below.

\begin{equation*} BMI = \frac{weight}{height^2} \end{equation*}

Interestingly, through the 485 initial responses, the researchers collecting the data discovered the dataset was extremely imbalanced (with a majority of the respondents falling into the normal category), so they decided to generate synthetic data (77% of the final dataset) using the Weka) data mining tool and SMOTE (synthetic minority over-sampling technique). After using this technique, a more balanced distribution was achieved. Therefore, much of the data processing was already handled for us by the researchers, and we started off with a relatively even dataset (as we will see below) [4].

The goal is to use the 17 different attributes collected to predict what category of weight (underweight, normal, some category of overweight, or some category of obese) someone will be given different factors about their eating, activity, and lives. This may provide a better model of obesity than the simple BMI model described above and typically used to diagnose obesity.

1.2 Cross-Product Features¶

A feature cross is a synthetic feature formed by crossing two or more features that may be correlated with the target variable. Crossing combinations of features can provide predictive abilities beyond what those features can provide individually.

Cross-Product Feature 1: Consumption of food between meals (CAEC) - Frequent consumption of high caloric food (FAVC)¶

The consumption of food between meals and the frequency of one consuming high-calorie food can help us know the eating habit of an individual. Typically, if one frequently consumes high caloric food and still consumes food between meals, he or she would take in more calories in a day compared to another person who is having a normal diet. Therefore, the individual has a higher chance of obesity.

Cross-Product Feature 2: Family_History - Consumption of alcohol (CALC)¶

People with a family history of obesity had a higher BMI and were at increased risk of obesity. Also, research shows that drinking alcohol increases appetite, and so can lead to overeating and weight gain. To be more specific, drinking more than seven times per week was associated with the risk of weight gain and the development of overweight. The product of Family History with Consumption of alcohol can help us identify one's risk of obesity. If one has a family history of obesity and consume alcohol regularly, he/she will have a higher risk of being obese.

Cross-Product Feature 3: Gender - Smoking (SMOKE)¶

Research has shown that current smokers have a lower mean body mass index (BMI) than never and former smokers, with former smokers having the highest mean BMI. Therefore, people who smoke often are more likely to be obese in a long run. Generally, males tend to use all tobacco products at higher rates than women. The product between Gender and Smoke can give us a model for how likely one will be obese from individual gender and smoking habit.

Cross-Product Feature 4: Frequent consumption of high caloric food (FAVC) - Calorie consumption monitoring (SCC)¶

Frequent consumption of high caloric food (FAVC) - Calories consumption monitoring (SCC) Tracking calorie intake can help one to identify which eating patterns he/she needs to modify to successfully lose weight. Similarly, an individual is more likely to be obese if he/she consumes high caloric food frequently. The product of frequent consumption of high caloric food (FAVC) with calorie consumption monitoring (SCC) can model the relationship of one’s eating habits. If one consumes high-calorie food very often and does track the calorie intake, he/she has a higher chance to be obese. On the other hand, if one consume high-calorie food less often and keep taking his/her calories, he/she is less likely to be obese.

Cross-Product Feature 5: Gender - Family History¶

The prevalence of overweight and obesity among men and women varies greatly between countries, but overall, more women are obese than men. Similarly, people with a family history of obesity had a higher BMI and were at increased risk of obesity. Using the product of both gender and family history, we can identify one’s risk of obesity. If one identified as female and has a family history of obesity, she would more likely to be obese.

1.3 Metric for Performance Evaluation¶

For evaluation, we want to know how precise the model is out of those predicted for each obesity category, how many of them are truly in that obesity category. We also want to know the fraction of the testing sample from a class that is correctly predicted by the model. In this scenario, the F-1 score is a great choice here because it is the harmonic mean of the precision and recall, which incorporates what we want to know.

Accuracy is usually the first metric to be used, but since we want to get a better measure of incorrectly classified cases, accuracy as a metric does not penalize wrong classifications enough. In our case, classifying someone as the wrong obesity / weight category could be very bad, especially if our model was used to dispense health data. A wrong classification could result in patients drastically changing their lifestyle and health, possibly to their detriment. Using the F-1 score will shed more light onto the false positives and negatives so that we can avoid these real-world ramifications.

The F-1 score is typically used for binary classification problems, but we can use it in a multi-class classification problem as well. To do this, we specify an averaging method so that we can get a single F-1 score for easier comparison. For this project, we are using the macro averaging method, which treats "all classes as equal, independent of the sample sizes." This ensures that the F-1 score of the majority class does not dominate.

If we had more time, we could have implemented a custom confusion matrix metric, where we could levy penalties for more egregious errors (i.e. classifying someone as Obesity_Type_III (the worst obesity level) if he / she was actually at the Normal_Weight level should be penalized much worse than classifying that person as Overweight_Type_1 (since Overweight_Type_1 is only the category right above Normal_Weight).

References:

  • https://medium.com/analytics-vidhya/accuracy-vs-f1-score-6258237beca2
  • https://www.baeldung.com/cs/multi-class-f1-score
\begin{equation*} {F1-Score} = \frac {2*Precision*Recall}{(Precision+Recall)}\end{equation*}

As we can see, there is an pretty even distribution of every category in the dataset, so an 80/20 split seems to be proper in this case. But we decided to use StratifiedShuffleSplit due to our dataset being relatively small. In addition, this will help us prevent bias from occurring in our train/test set. Since StratifiedShuffleSplit will preserve the ratio of each class sample, we can prevent one class from being over/under represented in any of the train/test set splits. The stratification will be useful with more real-world training data as well, where there will be more severe class imbalance than in the current dataset, which has been artificially augmented using SMOTE to preserve class balance.

from copy import deepcopy
from sklearn.preprocessing import StandardScaler

def preprocess_data(X_train_orig, X_test_orig, y_train_orig, y_test_orig):
    X_train = deepcopy(X_train_orig)
    X_test = deepcopy(X_test_orig)
    
    # scale continuous numeric variables
    for col in numerical_cols:
        X_train[col] = X_train[col].astype(np.float32)
        X_test[col] = X_test[col].astype(np.float32)

        ss = StandardScaler()
        X_train[col] = ss.fit_transform(X_train[col].values.reshape(-1, 1))
        X_test[col] = ss.transform(X_test[col].values.reshape(-1, 1))
    
    # temporarily encode categorical features as integers (treat as one-hot-encoded later with embeddings)
    encoders = {}
    for col in categorical_cols:
        encoders[col] = LabelEncoder()
        X_train[col] = encoders[col].fit_transform(X_train[col])
        X_test[col] = encoders[col].transform(X_test[col])

    # convert target variable column values to numerical representation
    y_train = deepcopy(y_train_orig)
    y_test = deepcopy(y_test_orig)
    
    return (X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test)

2. Modeling¶

In this section, we will be creating five wide and deep networks. Each one is based off of wide and deep network architecture discussed in class, with the wide branch consisting of the cross-product feature embeddings, and the deep branch consisting of the categorical feature embeddings and continuous numeric dense layers. We will also be comparing the performance of a multi-layer perceptron architecture with our best-performing wide and deep architecture.

  1. MLP: 3 Deep Layers
  2. WD Network 1: 3 Deep Layers, 3 Crossed Columns (['FAVC', 'CAEC'], ['Family_History', 'CALC'], ['FAVC', 'SCC'])
  3. WD Network 2: 3 Deep Layers, 5 Crossed Columns (['FAVC', 'CAEC'], ['Family_History', 'CALC'], ['FAVC', 'SCC'], ['Gender', 'SMOKE'], ['Gender', 'Family_History'])
  4. WD Network 1: 3 Deep Layers (with 2x # of neurons), 3 Crossed Columns (['FAVC', 'CAEC'], ['Family_History', 'CALC'], ['FAVC', 'SCC'])
  5. WD Network 1: 5 Deep Layers, 3 Crossed Columns (['FAVC', 'CAEC'], ['Family_History', 'CALC'], ['FAVC', 'SCC'])
  6. WD Network 1: 7 Deep Layers, 3 Crossed Columns (['FAVC', 'CAEC'], ['Family_History', 'CALC'], ['FAVC', 'SCC'])

2.1 Multi-Layer Perceptron (MLP)¶

In [14]:
def create_mlp(X_train, X_test):
    # save all mlp layer inputs and layers
    all_mlp_inputs = []
    all_mlp_layers = []
    
    # get numeric feature values
    X_train_num = X_train[numerical_cols].to_numpy()
    X_test_num = X_test[numerical_cols].to_numpy()
    
    # get categorical inputs and outputs
    X_train_cat = []
    X_test_cat = []

    for idx, col in enumerate(categorical_cols):
        X_train_cat.append(X_train[col].to_numpy())
        X_test_cat.append(X_test[col].to_numpy())

        # save max integer value, select cat values, and get embeddings
        N = max(X_train[col].max(), X_test[col].max()) + 1
        inputs = Input(shape=(1,), dtype='int32', name=col)
        all_mlp_inputs.append(inputs)
        x = Embedding(input_dim=N, output_dim=int(np.sqrt(N)), input_length=1, name=col+'_embed')(inputs)
        x = Flatten()(x)

        all_mlp_layers.append(x)
        
    # create numeric data input and layer
    input_num = Input(shape=(X_train_num.shape[1],), sparse=False, name='numeric_inputs')
    x_num = Dense(units=15, activation='relu', name='numeric_1')(input_num)

    all_mlp_inputs.append(input_num)
    all_mlp_layers.append(x_num)
    
    # concatenate outputs and add a fully connected layer
    final_branch = concatenate(all_mlp_layers, name='concat_1')
    final_branch = Dense(units=50, activation='relu')(final_branch)
    final_branch = Dense(units=25, activation='relu')(final_branch)
    final_branch = Dense(units=10, activation='relu')(final_branch)
    output = Dense(7, activation='softmax')(final_branch)
    
    # define model
    model_mlp = Model(inputs=all_mlp_inputs, outputs=output)
    
    return model_mlp, X_train_cat, X_train_num, X_test_cat, X_test_num
In [15]:
# compute all mlp scores
from sklearn.preprocessing import OneHotEncoder

mlp_scores = []
mlp_models = []
mlp_histories = []

for X_train_orig, X_test_orig, y_train_orig, y_test_orig in splits:
    X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = preprocess_data(X_train_orig, X_test_orig, y_train_orig, y_test_orig)

    mlp_model, X_train_cat, X_train_num, X_test_cat, X_test_num = create_mlp(X_train, X_test)
    mlp_model.compile(loss='categorical_crossentropy', optimizer='adam', metrics=[f1])
    
    y_train_enc = y_train.reshape(len(y_train), 1)
    y_train_enc = y_ohe_encoder.transform(y_train_enc)
    y_test_enc = y_test.reshape(len(y_test), 1)
    y_test_enc = y_ohe_encoder.transform(y_test_enc)

    mlp_history = mlp_model.fit(X_train_cat + [X_train_num], y_train_enc, epochs=20, batch_size=32, verbose=1,
                        validation_data = (X_test_cat + [X_test_num], y_test_enc))
    
    mlp_models.append(mlp_model)
    mlp_histories.append(mlp_history)
    
    scores = mlp_model.evaluate(X_test_cat + [X_test_num], y_test_enc, verbose=0)
    mlp_scores.append(scores)

2.2 Wide & Deep Networks¶

2.2.1. Wide & Deep Network 1 (Base Model) - 3 Deep Layers, 3 Crossed Columns¶

In [20]:
def create_wide_and_deep_network_1(X_train, X_test):
    X_num_train = X_train[numerical_cols].values
    X_num_test = X_test[numerical_cols].values
    
    # save feature inputs to model
    X_cat_train = []
    X_cat_test = []

    # set crossed columns
    cross_columns = cross_columns_subset

    # cross all sets of columns
    cross_col_names = []
    for cols in cross_columns:
        # encode crossed column values as integers
        enc = LabelEncoder()

        X_crossed_train = X_train_orig[cols].apply(lambda x: '_'.join(x), axis=1)
        X_crossed_test = X_test_orig[cols].apply(lambda x: '_'.join(x), axis=1)

        enc.fit(np.hstack((X_crossed_train.to_numpy(), X_crossed_test.to_numpy())))

        # save into dataframe with new name
        cross_col_name = '_'.join(cols)
        X_train[cross_col_name] = enc.transform(X_crossed_train)
        X_test[cross_col_name] = enc.transform(X_crossed_test)
        X_cat_train.append(enc.transform(X_crossed_train))
        X_cat_test.append(enc.transform(X_crossed_test))

        cross_col_names.append(cross_col_name)

    # save crossed features
    X_train_crossed = X_train[cross_col_names].to_numpy()
    X_test_crossed = X_test[cross_col_names].to_numpy()

    # save categorical features
    X_train_cat = X_train[categorical_cols].to_numpy() 
    X_test_cat = X_test[categorical_cols].to_numpy() 

    # save numeric features
    X_train_num =  X_train[numerical_cols].to_numpy()
    X_test_num = X_test[numerical_cols].to_numpy()
    
    all_inputs = []

    # WIDE BRANCH - crossed data input
    wide_branch_outputs = []

    for idx, col in enumerate(cross_col_names):    
        N = max(X_train[col].max(), X_test[col].max()) + 1

        # create / save crossed column inputs and embeddings
        inputs = Input(shape=(1,), dtype='int32', name=col)
        all_inputs.append(inputs)
        x = Embedding(input_dim=N, output_dim=int(np.sqrt(N)), input_length=1, name=col+'_embed')(inputs)
        x = Flatten()(x)

        wide_branch_outputs.append(x)

    # concatenate embeddings
    wide_branch = concatenate(wide_branch_outputs, name='wide_concat')
    wide_branch = Dense(units=15, activation='relu', name='wide_combined')(wide_branch)
    
    # DEEP BRANCH

    # deep network - categorical data input
    deep_branch_outputs = []

    for idx, col in enumerate(categorical_cols):
        X_cat_train.append(X_train[col].values)
        X_cat_test.append(X_test[col].values)

        # create / save categorical data inputs and embeddings
        N = max(X_train[col].max(), X_test[col].max()) + 1
        inputs = Input(shape=(1,), dtype='int32', name=col)
        all_inputs.append(inputs)
        x = Embedding(input_dim=N, output_dim=int(np.sqrt(N)), input_length=1, name=col+'_embed')(inputs)
        x = Flatten()(x)

        deep_branch_outputs.append(x)

    # deep network - numeric data input
    # create / save numeric data inputs and dense layer
    input_num = Input(shape=(X_train_num.shape[1],), name='numeric_inputs')
    all_inputs.append(input_num)

    x_dense = Dense(units=15, activation='relu', name='numeric_dense')(input_num)
    deep_branch_outputs.append(x_dense)
    
    # merge deep branches together
    deep_branch = concatenate(deep_branch_outputs, name='concat_deep')
    deep_branch = Dense(units=50, activation='relu', name='deep1')(deep_branch)
    deep_branch = Dense(units=25, activation='relu', name='deep2')(deep_branch)
    deep_branch = Dense(units=10, activation='relu', name='deep3')(deep_branch)

    # merge wide and deep branches together
    final_branch = concatenate([wide_branch, deep_branch], name='concat_deep_wide')
    final_branch = Dense(units=7, activation='softmax', name='combined')(final_branch)
    
    model = Model(inputs=all_inputs, outputs=final_branch, name='model1')
    
    return model, X_cat_train, X_num_train, X_cat_test, X_num_test

# compute cross validation scores across all folds

X_num_train = X_train[numerical_cols].values
X_num_test = X_test[numerical_cols].values

wd_model1_scores = []
wd_model1_models = []
wd_model1_histories = []

for X_train_orig, X_test_orig, y_train_orig, y_test_orig in splits:
    X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = preprocess_data(X_train_orig, X_test_orig, y_train_orig, y_test_orig)
    
    model1, X_cat_train, X_num_train, X_cat_test, X_num_test = create_wide_and_deep_network_1(X_train, X_test)
    model1.compile(optimizer='adam',
                  loss='categorical_crossentropy',
                  metrics=[f1])
    
    y_train_enc = y_train.reshape(len(y_train), 1)
    y_train_enc = y_ohe_encoder.transform(y_train_enc)
    y_test_enc = y_test.reshape(len(y_test), 1)
    y_test_enc = y_ohe_encoder.transform(y_test_enc)

    history = model1.fit(X_cat_train + [X_num_train],
                    y_train_enc, 
                    epochs=20, 
                    batch_size=32, 
                    verbose=1, 
                    validation_data = (X_cat_test + [X_num_test], y_test_enc))
    
    wd_model1_models.append(model1)
    wd_model1_histories.append(history)
    
    scores = model1.evaluate(X_cat_test + [X_num_test], y_test_enc, verbose=0)
    wd_model1_scores.append(scores)

2.2.2. Wide & Deep Network 2 - 3 Deep Layers, 5 Crossed Columns¶

In [26]:
def create_wide_and_deep_network_2(X_train, X_test):
    X_num_train = X_train[numerical_cols].values
    X_num_test = X_test[numerical_cols].values
    
    # save feature inputs to model
    X_cat_train = []
    X_cat_test = []

    # set crossed columns
    cross_columns = cross_columns_all

    # cross all sets of columns
    cross_col_names = []
    for cols in cross_columns:
        # encode crossed column values as integers
        enc = LabelEncoder()

        X_crossed_train = X_train_orig[cols].apply(lambda x: '_'.join(x), axis=1)
        X_crossed_test = X_test_orig[cols].apply(lambda x: '_'.join(x), axis=1)

        enc.fit(np.hstack((X_crossed_train.to_numpy(), X_crossed_test.to_numpy())))

        # save into dataframe with new name
        cross_col_name = '_'.join(cols)
        X_train[cross_col_name] = enc.transform(X_crossed_train)
        X_test[cross_col_name] = enc.transform(X_crossed_test)
        X_cat_train.append(enc.transform(X_crossed_train))
        X_cat_test.append(enc.transform(X_crossed_test))

        cross_col_names.append(cross_col_name)

    # save crossed features
    X_train_crossed = X_train[cross_col_names].to_numpy()
    X_test_crossed = X_test[cross_col_names].to_numpy()

    # save categorical features
    X_train_cat = X_train[categorical_cols].to_numpy() 
    X_test_cat = X_test[categorical_cols].to_numpy() 

    # save numeric features
    X_train_num =  X_train[numerical_cols].to_numpy()
    X_test_num = X_test[numerical_cols].to_numpy()
    
    all_inputs = []

    # WIDE BRANCH - crossed data input
    wide_branch_outputs = []

    for idx, col in enumerate(cross_col_names):    
        N = max(X_train[col].max(), X_test[col].max()) + 1

        # create / save crossed column inputs and embeddings
        inputs = Input(shape=(1,), dtype='int32', name=col)
        all_inputs.append(inputs)
        x = Embedding(input_dim=N, output_dim=int(np.sqrt(N)), input_length=1, name=col+'_embed')(inputs)
        x = Flatten()(x)

        wide_branch_outputs.append(x)

    # concatenate embeddings
    wide_branch = concatenate(wide_branch_outputs, name='wide_concat')
    wide_branch = Dense(units=15, activation='relu', name='wide_combined')(wide_branch)
    
    # DEEP BRANCH

    # deep network - categorical data input
    deep_branch_outputs = []

    for idx, col in enumerate(categorical_cols):
        X_cat_train.append(X_train[col].values)
        X_cat_test.append(X_test[col].values)

        # create / save categorical data inputs and embeddings
        N = max(X_train[col].max(), X_test[col].max()) + 1
        inputs = Input(shape=(1,), dtype='int32', name=col)
        all_inputs.append(inputs)
        x = Embedding(input_dim=N, output_dim=int(np.sqrt(N)), input_length=1, name=col+'_embed')(inputs)
        x = Flatten()(x)

        deep_branch_outputs.append(x)

    # deep network - numeric data input
    # create / save numeric data inputs and dense layer
    input_num = Input(shape=(X_train_num.shape[1],), name='numeric_inputs')
    all_inputs.append(input_num)

    x_dense = Dense(units=15, activation='relu', name='numeric_dense')(input_num)
    deep_branch_outputs.append(x_dense)
    
    # merge deep branches together
    deep_branch = concatenate(deep_branch_outputs, name='concat_deep')
    deep_branch = Dense(units=50, activation='relu', name='deep1')(deep_branch)
    deep_branch = Dense(units=25, activation='relu', name='deep2')(deep_branch)
    deep_branch = Dense(units=10, activation='relu', name='deep3')(deep_branch)

    # merge wide and deep branches together
    final_branch = concatenate([wide_branch, deep_branch], name='concat_deep_wide')
    final_branch = Dense(units=7, activation='softmax', name='combined')(final_branch)
    
    model = Model(inputs=all_inputs, outputs=final_branch, name='model2')
    
    return model, X_cat_train, X_num_train, X_cat_test, X_num_test

# compute cross validation scores across all folds

wd_model2_scores = []
wd_model2_models = []
wd_model2_histories = []

for X_train_orig, X_test_orig, y_train_orig, y_test_orig in splits:
    X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = preprocess_data(X_train_orig, X_test_orig, y_train_orig, y_test_orig)
    
    model2, X_cat_train, X_num_train, X_cat_test, X_num_test = create_wide_and_deep_network_2(X_train, X_test)
    model2.compile(optimizer='adam',
                  loss='categorical_crossentropy',
                  metrics=[f1])
    
    y_train_enc = y_train.reshape(len(y_train), 1)
    y_train_enc = y_ohe_encoder.transform(y_train_enc)
    y_test_enc = y_test.reshape(len(y_test), 1)
    y_test_enc = y_ohe_encoder.transform(y_test_enc)

    history = model2.fit(X_cat_train + [X_num_train],
                    y_train_enc, 
                    epochs=20, 
                    batch_size=32, 
                    verbose=1, 
                    validation_data = (X_cat_test + [X_num_test], y_test_enc))
    
    wd_model2_models.append(model2)
    wd_model2_histories.append(history)
    
    scores = model2.evaluate(X_cat_test + [X_num_test], y_test_enc, verbose=0)
    wd_model2_scores.append(scores)

2.2.3. Wide & Deep Network 3 - 3 Deep Layers (with 2x # of neurons), 3 Crossed Columns¶

In [32]:
def create_wide_and_deep_network_3(X_train, X_test):
    X_num_train = X_train[numerical_cols].values
    X_num_test = X_test[numerical_cols].values
    
    # save feature inputs to model
    X_cat_train = []
    X_cat_test = []

    # set crossed columns
    cross_columns = cross_columns_subset

    # cross all sets of columns
    cross_col_names = []
    for cols in cross_columns:
        # encode crossed column values as integers
        enc = LabelEncoder()

        X_crossed_train = X_train_orig[cols].apply(lambda x: '_'.join(x), axis=1)
        X_crossed_test = X_test_orig[cols].apply(lambda x: '_'.join(x), axis=1)

        enc.fit(np.hstack((X_crossed_train.to_numpy(), X_crossed_test.to_numpy())))

        # save into dataframe with new name
        cross_col_name = '_'.join(cols)
        X_train[cross_col_name] = enc.transform(X_crossed_train)
        X_test[cross_col_name] = enc.transform(X_crossed_test)
        X_cat_train.append(enc.transform(X_crossed_train))
        X_cat_test.append(enc.transform(X_crossed_test))

        cross_col_names.append(cross_col_name)

    # save crossed features
    X_train_crossed = X_train[cross_col_names].to_numpy()
    X_test_crossed = X_test[cross_col_names].to_numpy()

    # save categorical features
    X_train_cat = X_train[categorical_cols].to_numpy() 
    X_test_cat = X_test[categorical_cols].to_numpy() 

    # save numeric features
    X_train_num =  X_train[numerical_cols].to_numpy()
    X_test_num = X_test[numerical_cols].to_numpy()
    
    all_inputs = []

    # WIDE BRANCH - crossed data input
    wide_branch_outputs = []

    for idx, col in enumerate(cross_col_names):    
        N = max(X_train[col].max(), X_test[col].max()) + 1

        # create / save crossed column inputs and embeddings
        inputs = Input(shape=(1,), dtype='int32', name=col)
        all_inputs.append(inputs)
        x = Embedding(input_dim=N, output_dim=int(np.sqrt(N)), input_length=1, name=col+'_embed')(inputs)
        x = Flatten()(x)

        wide_branch_outputs.append(x)

    # concatenate embeddings
    wide_branch = concatenate(wide_branch_outputs, name='wide_concat')
    wide_branch = Dense(units=30, activation='relu', name='wide_combined')(wide_branch)
    
    # DEEP BRANCH

    # deep network - categorical data input
    deep_branch_outputs = []

    for idx, col in enumerate(categorical_cols):
        X_cat_train.append(X_train[col].values)
        X_cat_test.append(X_test[col].values)

        # create / save categorical data inputs and embeddings
        N = max(X_train[col].max(), X_test[col].max()) + 1
        inputs = Input(shape=(1,), dtype='int32', name=col)
        all_inputs.append(inputs)
        x = Embedding(input_dim=N, output_dim=int(np.sqrt(N)), input_length=1, name=col+'_embed')(inputs)
        x = Flatten()(x)

        deep_branch_outputs.append(x)

    # deep network - numeric data input
    # create / save numeric data inputs and dense layer
    input_num = Input(shape=(X_train_num.shape[1],), name='numeric_inputs')
    all_inputs.append(input_num)

    x_dense = Dense(units=15, activation='relu', name='numeric_dense')(input_num)
    deep_branch_outputs.append(x_dense)
    
    # merge deep branches together
    deep_branch = concatenate(deep_branch_outputs, name='concat_deep')
    deep_branch = Dense(units=100, activation='relu', name='deep1')(deep_branch)
    deep_branch = Dense(units=50, activation='relu', name='deep2')(deep_branch)
    deep_branch = Dense(units=20, activation='relu', name='deep3')(deep_branch)

    # merge wide and deep branches together
    final_branch = concatenate([wide_branch, deep_branch], name='concat_deep_wide')
    final_branch = Dense(units=7, activation='softmax', name='combined')(final_branch)
    
    model = Model(inputs=all_inputs, outputs=final_branch, name='model2')
    
    return model, X_cat_train, X_num_train, X_cat_test, X_num_test

# compute cross validation scores across all folds

wd_model3_scores = []
wd_model3_models = []
wd_model3_histories = []

for X_train_orig, X_test_orig, y_train_orig, y_test_orig in splits:
    X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = preprocess_data(X_train_orig, X_test_orig, y_train_orig, y_test_orig)
    
    model3, X_cat_train, X_num_train, X_cat_test, X_num_test = create_wide_and_deep_network_3(X_train, X_test)
    model3.compile(optimizer='adam',
                  loss='categorical_crossentropy',
                  metrics=[f1])
    
    y_train_enc = y_train.reshape(len(y_train), 1)
    y_train_enc = y_ohe_encoder.transform(y_train_enc)
    y_test_enc = y_test.reshape(len(y_test), 1)
    y_test_enc = y_ohe_encoder.transform(y_test_enc)

    history = model3.fit(X_cat_train + [X_num_train],
                    y_train_enc, 
                    epochs=20, 
                    batch_size=32, 
                    verbose=1, 
                    validation_data = (X_cat_test + [X_num_test], y_test_enc))
        
    wd_model3_models.append(model3)
    wd_model3_histories.append(history)
    
    scores = model3.evaluate(X_cat_test + [X_num_test], y_test_enc, verbose=0)
    wd_model3_scores.append(scores)

2.2.4. Wide & Deep Network 4 - 5 Deep Layers, 3 Crossed Columns¶

In [38]:
def create_wide_and_deep_network_4(X_train, X_test):
    X_num_train = X_train[numerical_cols].values
    X_num_test = X_test[numerical_cols].values
    
    # save feature inputs to model
    X_cat_train = []
    X_cat_test = []

    # set crossed columns
    cross_columns = cross_columns_subset

    # cross all sets of columns
    cross_col_names = []
    for cols in cross_columns:
        # encode crossed column values as integers
        enc = LabelEncoder()

        X_crossed_train = X_train_orig[cols].apply(lambda x: '_'.join(x), axis=1)
        X_crossed_test = X_test_orig[cols].apply(lambda x: '_'.join(x), axis=1)

        enc.fit(np.hstack((X_crossed_train.to_numpy(), X_crossed_test.to_numpy())))

        # save into dataframe with new name
        cross_col_name = '_'.join(cols)
        X_train[cross_col_name] = enc.transform(X_crossed_train)
        X_test[cross_col_name] = enc.transform(X_crossed_test)
        X_cat_train.append(enc.transform(X_crossed_train))
        X_cat_test.append(enc.transform(X_crossed_test))

        cross_col_names.append(cross_col_name)

    # save crossed features
    X_train_crossed = X_train[cross_col_names].to_numpy()
    X_test_crossed = X_test[cross_col_names].to_numpy()

    # save categorical features
    X_train_cat = X_train[categorical_cols].to_numpy() 
    X_test_cat = X_test[categorical_cols].to_numpy() 

    # save numeric features
    X_train_num =  X_train[numerical_cols].to_numpy()
    X_test_num = X_test[numerical_cols].to_numpy()
    
    all_inputs = []

    # WIDE BRANCH - crossed data input
    wide_branch_outputs = []

    for idx, col in enumerate(cross_col_names):    
        N = max(X_train[col].max(), X_test[col].max()) + 1

        # create / save crossed column inputs and embeddings
        inputs = Input(shape=(1,), dtype='int32', name=col)
        all_inputs.append(inputs)
        x = Embedding(input_dim=N, output_dim=int(np.sqrt(N)), input_length=1, name=col+'_embed')(inputs)
        x = Flatten()(x)

        wide_branch_outputs.append(x)

    # concatenate embeddings
    wide_branch = concatenate(wide_branch_outputs, name='wide_concat')
    wide_branch = Dense(units=15, activation='relu', name='wide_combined')(wide_branch)
    
    # DEEP BRANCH

    # deep network - categorical data input
    deep_branch_outputs = []

    for idx, col in enumerate(categorical_cols):
        X_cat_train.append(X_train[col].values)
        X_cat_test.append(X_test[col].values)

        # create / save categorical data inputs and embeddings
        N = max(X_train[col].max(), X_test[col].max()) + 1
        inputs = Input(shape=(1,), dtype='int32', name=col)
        all_inputs.append(inputs)
        x = Embedding(input_dim=N, output_dim=int(np.sqrt(N)), input_length=1, name=col+'_embed')(inputs)
        x = Flatten()(x)

        deep_branch_outputs.append(x)

    # deep network - numeric data input
    # create / save numeric data inputs and dense layer
    input_num = Input(shape=(X_train_num.shape[1],), name='numeric_inputs')
    all_inputs.append(input_num)

    x_dense = Dense(units=15, activation='relu', name='numeric_dense')(input_num)
    deep_branch_outputs.append(x_dense)
    
    # merge deep branches together
    deep_branch = concatenate(deep_branch_outputs, name='concat_deep')
    
    # CHANGE NUMBER OF BRANCHES IN DEEP NETWORK
    deep_branch = Dense(units=50, activation='relu', name='deep1')(deep_branch)
    deep_branch = Dense(units=50, activation='relu', name='deep2')(deep_branch)
    deep_branch = Dense(units=25, activation='relu', name='deep3')(deep_branch)
    deep_branch = Dense(units=25, activation='relu', name='deep4')(deep_branch)
    deep_branch = Dense(units=10, activation='relu', name='deep5')(deep_branch)

    # merge wide and deep branches together
    final_branch = concatenate([wide_branch, deep_branch], name='concat_deep_wide')
    final_branch = Dense(units=7, activation='softmax', name='combined')(final_branch)
    
    model = Model(inputs=all_inputs, outputs=final_branch, name='model4')
    
    return model, X_cat_train, X_num_train, X_cat_test, X_num_test

# compute cross validation scores across all folds

wd_model4_scores = []
wd_model4_models = []
wd_model4_histories = []

for X_train_orig, X_test_orig, y_train_orig, y_test_orig in splits:
    X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = preprocess_data(X_train_orig, X_test_orig, y_train_orig, y_test_orig)
    
    model4, X_cat_train, X_num_train, X_cat_test, X_num_test = create_wide_and_deep_network_4(X_train, X_test)
    model4.compile(optimizer='adam',
                  loss='categorical_crossentropy',
                  metrics=[f1])
    
    y_train_enc = y_train.reshape(len(y_train), 1)
    y_train_enc = y_ohe_encoder.transform(y_train_enc)
    y_test_enc = y_test.reshape(len(y_test), 1)
    y_test_enc = y_ohe_encoder.transform(y_test_enc)

    history = model4.fit(X_cat_train + [X_num_train],
                    y_train_enc, 
                    epochs=20, 
                    batch_size=32, 
                    verbose=1, 
                    validation_data = (X_cat_test + [X_num_test], y_test_enc))
    
    wd_model4_models.append(model4)
    wd_model4_histories.append(history)
    
    scores = model4.evaluate(X_cat_test + [X_num_test], y_test_enc, verbose=0)
    wd_model4_scores.append(scores)

2.2.5 Wide & Deep Network 5 - 7 Deep Layers, 3 Crossed Columns¶

In [44]:
def create_wide_and_deep_network_5(X_train, X_test):
    X_num_train = X_train[numerical_cols].values
    X_num_test = X_test[numerical_cols].values
    
    # save feature inputs to model
    X_cat_train = []
    X_cat_test = []

    # set crossed columns
    cross_columns = cross_columns_subset

    # cross all sets of columns
    cross_col_names = []
    for cols in cross_columns:
        # encode crossed column values as integers
        enc = LabelEncoder()

        X_crossed_train = X_train_orig[cols].apply(lambda x: '_'.join(x), axis=1)
        X_crossed_test = X_test_orig[cols].apply(lambda x: '_'.join(x), axis=1)

        enc.fit(np.hstack((X_crossed_train.to_numpy(), X_crossed_test.to_numpy())))

        # save into dataframe with new name
        cross_col_name = '_'.join(cols)
        X_train[cross_col_name] = enc.transform(X_crossed_train)
        X_test[cross_col_name] = enc.transform(X_crossed_test)
        X_cat_train.append(enc.transform(X_crossed_train))
        X_cat_test.append(enc.transform(X_crossed_test))

        cross_col_names.append(cross_col_name)

    # save crossed features
    X_train_crossed = X_train[cross_col_names].to_numpy()
    X_test_crossed = X_test[cross_col_names].to_numpy()

    # save categorical features
    X_train_cat = X_train[categorical_cols].to_numpy() 
    X_test_cat = X_test[categorical_cols].to_numpy() 

    # save numeric features
    X_train_num =  X_train[numerical_cols].to_numpy()
    X_test_num = X_test[numerical_cols].to_numpy()
    
    all_inputs = []

    # WIDE BRANCH - crossed data input
    wide_branch_outputs = []

    for idx, col in enumerate(cross_col_names):    
        N = max(X_train[col].max(), X_test[col].max()) + 1

        # create / save crossed column inputs and embeddings
        inputs = Input(shape=(1,), dtype='int32', name=col)
        all_inputs.append(inputs)
        x = Embedding(input_dim=N, output_dim=int(np.sqrt(N)), input_length=1, name=col+'_embed')(inputs)
        x = Flatten()(x)

        wide_branch_outputs.append(x)

    # concatenate embeddings
    wide_branch = concatenate(wide_branch_outputs, name='wide_concat')
    wide_branch = Dense(units=15, activation='relu', name='wide_combined')(wide_branch)
    
    # DEEP BRANCH

    # deep network - categorical data input
    deep_branch_outputs = []

    for idx, col in enumerate(categorical_cols):
        X_cat_train.append(X_train[col].values)
        X_cat_test.append(X_test[col].values)

        # create / save categorical data inputs and embeddings
        N = max(X_train[col].max(), X_test[col].max()) + 1
        inputs = Input(shape=(1,), dtype='int32', name=col)
        all_inputs.append(inputs)
        x = Embedding(input_dim=N, output_dim=int(np.sqrt(N)), input_length=1, name=col+'_embed')(inputs)
        x = Flatten()(x)

        deep_branch_outputs.append(x)

    # deep network - numeric data input
    # create / save numeric data inputs and dense layer
    input_num = Input(shape=(X_train_num.shape[1],), name='numeric_inputs')
    all_inputs.append(input_num)

    x_dense = Dense(units=15, activation='relu', name='numeric_dense')(input_num)
    deep_branch_outputs.append(x_dense)
    
    # merge deep branches together
    deep_branch = concatenate(deep_branch_outputs, name='concat_deep')
    
    # CHANGE NUMBER OF BRANCHES IN DEEP NETWORK
    deep_branch = Dense(units=100, activation='relu', name='deep1')(deep_branch)
    deep_branch = Dense(units=50, activation='relu', name='deep2')(deep_branch)
    deep_branch = Dense(units=50, activation='relu', name='deep3')(deep_branch)
    deep_branch = Dense(units=25, activation='relu', name='deep4')(deep_branch)
    deep_branch = Dense(units=25, activation='relu', name='deep5')(deep_branch)
    deep_branch = Dense(units=10, activation='relu', name='deep6')(deep_branch)
    deep_branch = Dense(units=10, activation='relu', name='deep7')(deep_branch)

    # merge wide and deep branches together
    final_branch = concatenate([wide_branch, deep_branch], name='concat_deep_wide')
    final_branch = Dense(units=7, activation='softmax', name='combined')(final_branch)
    
    model = Model(inputs=all_inputs, outputs=final_branch, name='model5')
    
    return model, X_cat_train, X_num_train, X_cat_test, X_num_test

# compute cross validation scores across all folds

wd_model5_scores = []
wd_model5_models = []
wd_model5_histories = []

for X_train_orig, X_test_orig, y_train_orig, y_test_orig in splits:
    X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = preprocess_data(X_train_orig, X_test_orig, y_train_orig, y_test_orig)
    
    model5, X_cat_train, X_num_train, X_cat_test, X_num_test = create_wide_and_deep_network_5(X_train, X_test)
    model5.compile(optimizer='adam',
                  loss='categorical_crossentropy',
                  metrics=[f1])
    
    y_train_enc = y_train.reshape(len(y_train), 1)
    y_train_enc = y_ohe_encoder.transform(y_train_enc)
    y_test_enc = y_test.reshape(len(y_test), 1)
    y_test_enc = y_ohe_encoder.transform(y_test_enc)

    history = model5.fit(X_cat_train + [X_num_train],
                    y_train_enc, 
                    epochs=20, 
                    batch_size=32, 
                    verbose=1, 
                    validation_data = (X_cat_test + [X_num_test], y_test_enc))
    
    wd_model5_models.append(model5)
    wd_model5_histories.append(history)
    
    scores = model5.evaluate(X_cat_test + [X_num_test], y_test_enc, verbose=0)
    wd_model5_scores.append(scores)

2.3 Compare model architectures with different numbers of deep branch layers¶

Here, we compare wide & deep models #1, #4, and #5, which only differ in the number of deep branch layers (3, 5, and 7 respectively) using the McNemar's statistical significance test. McNemar's test is a statistical signifiance test that can be used to compare the performance of different machine learning models. The test is "recommended in those cases where the algorithms being compared can only be evaluated once" [ref]. We use this test to determine whether one model's performance is significantly different from another model's performance by calculating a contingency table and comparing the calculated pvalue to a specified alpha.

Reference: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/McNemar%27s_test

In [50]:
def calculate_contingency_table(cl1_array, cl2_array):
    table = np.zeros((2, 2))
    
    # [[both correct, cl1 correct and cl2 wrong]
    # [cl2 correct and cl1 wrong, both cl1 and cl2 wrong]]
    
    for r1, r2 in zip(cl1_array, cl2_array):
        if r1 and r2:
            table[0][0] += 1
        elif r1 and not r2:
            table[0][1] += 1
        elif not r1 and r2:
            table[1][0] += 1
        else:
            table[1][1] += 1
            
    return table

from statsmodels.stats.contingency_tables import mcnemar
alpha = 0.05

# code adapted from https://machinelearningmastery.com/mcnemars-test-for-machine-learning/
def mcnemar_test(table):
    # calculate mcnemar test from contingency table and print out statistical results
    result = mcnemar(table, exact=True)
    print('statistic=%.3f, p-value=%.3f' % (result.statistic, result.pvalue))

    # interpret the p-value
    if result.pvalue > alpha:
        print('Same proportions of errors (fail to reject H0)')
    else:
        print('Different proportions of errors (reject H0)')

The McNemar test demonstrates that models 1, 4, and 5 are all statistically different from one another. The contingency matrices printed above show that model 1 is correct more when the other two models are wrong compared to the instances in which the other two models are correct when model 1 is wrong. Because of this, we select model 1 as the best in terms of number of deep layers (3) to include.

2.3 Compare MLP vs. Best Wide & Deep Model¶

Here, we compare our MLP and best wide & deep model (#1) using the receiver operating characteristic and area under the curve values. The ROC curve shows the performance of a classification model at all classification thresholds based on true positive and false positive rates at different classification thresholds. The area under the curve (or AUC) is the area under the ROC curve and "provides an aggregate measure of perofmrance across all possible classification thresholds." Generally, the greater the AUC is, the better the model is.

We plot the micro-averaged ROC curves across all classes for the multiclass classification problem.

References: https://developers.google.com/machine-learning/crash-course/classification/roc-and-auc

After applying t-SNE to the layer embeddings and plotting them. A cluster can be seen that is made from the CAEC, CALC, and MTRANS categories. CAEC stands for consumption of food between meals, CALC stands for consumption of alcohol, and MTrans stands for transportation used. This cluster means that these 3 categories are closely related to each other and implies that they can be used to predict if someone is underweight, normal weight, overweight, and obese. As for the categories that are further away like the smoking and family history categories, it means that they have less in common with those in or near the cluster. Therefore they are less likely to determine if a person is underweight, normal weight, overweight, or obese.
